==English==

{{rfv}}
====Etymology====
A combination of the [[indefinite article]] "[[a]]" and "[[lot]]" 

===Adverb===
'''alot'''
# very [[many]]
#:''They have '''alot''' of things in their bag.''
# very [[much]]
#:''Thanks '''alot''' for helping me out.''
# [[often]]
#:''Yes, he does that '''alot'''.''

===Usage===
In all senses, a '''non-standard''' spelling of '''‘a [[lot]],’''' frequent in informal writing.

The ''American Heritage&reg; Book of English Usage'' states that “''alot'' is still considered an error in print” but notes that standard words have formed by fusion of the article with a noun, such as ''[[another]]'' and ''[[awhile]],'' and suggests the possibility that ''alot'' may like them eventually enter standard usage.  [http://www.bartleby.com/64/C003/0200.html]

===Quotations===
* '''2000:''' There was '''alot''' of sex discrimination in the 60’s. For one thing there was no sports for girls and in '''alot''' of schools the female teachers were not allowed to get married or they could be fired.  —''Teaching Secondary English,'' ed. Daniel Sheridan.  [in a tenth-grade student's paper] [http://print.google.com/print?id=ejtdcf-taQkC&pg=PA346&lpg=PA346&sig=t0Sp87KqxsH-UGYklzl72NMUz1Q]
* '''2003:''' It was '''alot''' of lumber, '''alot''' of condos, and Joe did not know '''alot''' about either of them, only that it was '''alot''' of money; he hated to throw his money into something he did not know '''alot''' about.  —Matt Janacone, ''Three by the Sea'' [http://print.google.com/print?id=CesAE2xl68QC&pg=PA107&lpg=PA107&sig=X8TjIfaBBBesXWW1E38K-BUtUPU] 
* '''2005:''' She talked about death: “My philosophy on life is it could be '''alot''' better. Like I would’ve never gotten into this mess if I wouldn’t have tried to commit suicide. Actually I was just trying to make myself sick. But then again it could be '''''alot''''' worse! [...]” —Aphrodite Jones, ''Cruel Sacrifice'' [http://print.google.com/print?id=KtlMQCtBzygC&pg=PA248&lpg=PA248&sig=2mA_bCMZr0l0dCLfhRWe4cBdmd4]